    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1952-10-20T06:30:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1952-10-20T06:30:00-05:00" n="948"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d948">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">446E.9331/10–2052: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Ceylon</hi> (<persName corresp="#p_SJC1"
                        type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Satterthwaite</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Department of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                    <note n="1" xml:id="d948fn1">This telegram was repeated to London for
                        information as telegram 21.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">secret</hi>
                    </seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Colombo</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1952-10-20T17:00:00+05:30"
                            >October 20, 1952—5 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>181. Min Food <persName>Goonetilleke</persName> today gave <persName
                        corresp="#p_BML1">Black</persName> in strictest confidence fol details re
                        <gloss target="#t_Chi1">Chi</gloss> rice-rubber proposal (<gloss
                        target="#t_Embtel1">Embtel</gloss> 179, Oct 20).<note n="2" xml:id="d948fn2"
                        >Telegram 179 from Colombo, not printed, quoted local newspapers reporting
                        on the details of the Ceylon-Chinese negotiations
                        (446E.9331/10–2052).</note>
                </p>
                <list>
                    <label>1.</label>
                    <item>
                        <gloss target="#t_Chi1">Chi</gloss> will supply 200,000 tons rice annually
                        at cost 56 pounds sterling per ton f.o.b. This will be in addition to 80,000
                        tons already agreed upon.</item>
                    <label>2.</label>
                    <item>
                        <gloss target="#t_Chi1">Chi</gloss> will buy any quantities No. 1, 2 and 3
                        sheet rubber offered up to 50,000 tons annually at average price of <gloss
                            target="#t_Rs1">Rs</gloss> 1.75 per pound f.o.b. In event world price
                        rises above <gloss target="#t_Rs1">Rs</gloss> 1.75 <gloss target="#t_GOC1"
                            >GOC</gloss> can renegotiate price. Rubber will continue to be sold
                        through Ceylon commercial channels.</item>
                    <label>3.</label>
                    <item>Although agreement theoretically for five years, quantities and prices of
                        both commodities will be negotiated annually.</item>
                    <label>4.</label>
                    <item>
                        <gloss target="#t_GOC1">GOC</gloss> has no intention permit <gloss
                            target="#t_Chi1">Chi</gloss> station either trade or diplomatic <gloss
                            target="#t_REP1">rep</gloss>s in Ceylon. Mission chief <persName
                            corresp="#p_SDS1">Senanayake</persName> rejected categorically <gloss
                            target="#t_Chi1">Chi</gloss> request permit <gloss target="#t_Chi1"
                            >Chi</gloss> agent reside Colombo to pass on rubber shipments.</item>
                </list>
                <p>
                    <persName>Goonetilleke</persName> said there is no question whatsoever but that
                    Cab will approve agreement and he himself has recommended such action. He asked
                    that in reporting matter to Wash <gloss target="#t_Emb1">Emb</gloss> shld
                    emphasize: <list>
                        <label>(<hi rend="italic">a</hi>)</label>
                        <item>
                            <gloss target="#t_GOC1">GOC</gloss> has no alternative but to sign
                            agreement. Providing rice for people is surest way to maintain present
                            govt and there is no danger of opposition parties taking over in
                            Ceylon.</item>
                        <label>(<hi rend="italic">b</hi>)</label>
                        <item>Signing of pact shld not be construed as indicating increase in <gloss
                                target="#t_GOC1">GOC</gloss>’s sympathy for Commies. <gloss
                                target="#t_GOC1">GOC</gloss> stands and will stand “staunchly on
                            side of West.”</item>
                    </list>
                </p>
                <p>
                    <persName>Goonetilleke</persName> said US “shld not worry over implications of
                    agreement as we in Ceylon have ways of slightly tricking our enemies.”</p>
                <p>According <persName>Goonetilleke</persName>, <gloss target="#t_Brit1"
                        >Brit</gloss> Consul General Peking informed mission chief <persName
                        corresp="#p_SDS1">Senanayake</persName> that <gloss target="#t_Chi1"
                        >Chi</gloss> use rubber for civilian purposes is expanding greatly and
                    obviously there is no shortage or restrictions on civilian use wld have been
                    imposed. This made strong impression on <persName corresp="#p_SDS1"
                        >Senanayake</persName> who used it in presenting proposals to Cab.</p>
                <pb facs="0496" n="1546" xml:id="pg_1546"/>
                <p>
                    <gloss target="#t_Emb1">Emb</gloss> considers such statements re “civilian”
                    consumption in Commie controlled economies to be meaningless. Furthermore,
                    statement inconsistent with <gloss target="#t_Chi1">Chi</gloss> willingness
                    contract year in advance pay premium price crude rubber.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_SJC1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Satterthwaite</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
